[1] Maldives
Date: Wed, 15 Feb 2006 09:42:12 -0500 (EST)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Hareeru Daily, Male, Maldives, 15 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://www.haveeru.com.mv/?page=engdetails&id=6834>

The Health Ministry has noted that the number of deaths caused by
Dengue Fever is increasing and that the number of infected is greatly
increasing in Male and the atolls.
Public Health's Director General Ibrahim Shaheem said that 2 children and one
man have died so far in 2006 because of the disease. The Health Ministry said
that 10-12 new cases are reported daily. This means that more than 300 new
cases are reported monthly.
Health Ministry's Medical Director Dr. Ahmed Raazee said Tuesday that
each day, at least 2 cases of the most dangerous forms of Dengue,
namely Dengue Hemorrhagic Fever and Dengue Hemorrhagic Shock, are
also reported.
The Ministry said that the number of those infected with the disease
is increasing throughout Maldives. The Ministry said that since
dangerous forms of dengue are being found, the number of fatalities
is also increasing. However fatality statistics were not disclosed.
The Health Ministry said that they are carrying out awareness
programs about the disease [which is] spread by a daytime-biting
mosquito and that those involved in treating the infected are being
informed of how to carry out the treatment and that [measures] are
being [taken] to control mosquitoes.
Dr. Raazee said that the public should be aware that if a medicine
other than Paracetamol is taken to lower fever, it could be
dangerous. "The best thing to do is to give Paracetamol. Then liquids
should be given," Dr. Raazee said.
"Ways to prevent mosquito bites should be found. For example mosquito
repellant sprays are available cheaply. Those should be used."
Special programs being planned to control dengue fever
------------------------------------------------------
Dengue fever is present in different parts of the Maldives, and
measures will be taken immediately to give protection from it, said
Public Health on Tuesday [7 Feb 2006].
Deputy Director General Ibrahim Shaheem said that dengue fever is a
danger that we must always be aware of and that appropriate measures
are being decided upon. "These measures will be in effect in about 2
days," he said.
Public Health records show that the percentage of people who have
sought treatment for dengue fever has remained constant for some
months now. Shaheem said that, on average, about 5 new cases of
dengue fever are reported every day.
"Among the people who have caught the fever, there is no one who is
seriously ill yet," he said. "It is children who catch dengue the
most."
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Note that 2 conflicting sets of statistics are given in this report: 10-12
cases per day including 2 cases of DHF/DSS -- a very high proportion -- and 5
cases a day, none serious. - Mod.JW]
[The Republic of Maldives is an island nation consisting of the
Maldive group of atolls and the Suvadive group of atolls in the
Indian Ocean, south of the Laccadive group of islands of India, about
700 kilometers southwest of Sri Lanka. For more details, see
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maldives>. - Mod.RY]
