[2] Australia
Date: Mon, 13 Feb 2006 11:23:47 -0500 (EST)
From: Dr. Alfonso J. Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Yahoo News. 14 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://townsvillebulletin.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,7034,18139048%
255E14787,00.html>

Queensland Health yesterday confirmed that there are now 7 cases of
dengue in the suburb, with the latest onsets of the illness reported
on 2 Feb and late January 2006.
The cases were found in 3 different streets in Cranbrook, with the
health authority yesterday issuing a warning in the area where the
cases were found, which includes Ross River Rd from Alice to Wattle
and Louise streets, and from Banksia and Cadiz courts to Gilli
Crescent and Jannila Avenue.
This follows an outbreak of the mosquito-borne disease in the area
between late December [2005] and mid-January [2006].
4 people from the same house, aged from 19 to 79, were affected by
the disease while another case was reported on 28 Jan 2006.
Townsville City Council Community Safety Committee chairwoman
Councillor Jenny Hill said council staff inspected 140 properties out
of 205 in the area, and 8 per cent were found to have mosquitoes
breeding on the premises.
"Most people have been good and helpful. If they're home they've made
sure the staff have had access, but the big problem is just trying to
reinforce that message that people need to check their own property,"
Cr Hill said. "If you are mowing your grass and you see containers
full of water, make sure you empty them."
She said residents should not be confused about any spraying for mosquitoes
the council was doing in other areas of Townsville. Following torrential rain
recently, the council undertook a concerted air and ground attack on saltmarsh
mosquitoes in freshwater and saltwater breeding sites in a 300-ha area
stretching from Cungulla to the Town Common and offshore to Magnetic Island.
"Any spraying we do or anything we do like that is useless for
dengue," Cr Hill said. "The dengue mosquito is a mosquito that
primarily exists in household areas, so we need householders to look
at potential breeding places. We talk about pot plant bases, paint
trays, bird baths, dog bowls, buckets and those sorts of things. It
requires a lot of manpower to manage, but everyone wants to get this
right, while mosquitoes are out there, to prevent dengue fever being
spread."
Cr Hill said there was no cause for alarm. "Residents shouldn't be
alarmed, they need to be careful, and they need to heed warnings from
public health and council, which are to check your back yards
regularly and remove any empty container that can hold water," she
said. "That way you can lessen the risk of contracting ... dengue fever."
There were 18 confirmed cases of dengue fever in Townsville last year
[2005], and one death in far north Queensland.
A dengue epidemic broke out in Townsville in the early 90s, leaving
900 people infected.
[Byline: Daniel Bateman]
