[4] Australia
Date: Mon, 13 Feb 2006 07:45:01 -0500 (EST)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: ABC Regional Online, 13 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/news/items/200602/1568228.htm?northqld>

The Tropical Population Health Unit is warning people to destroy
mosquito breeding sites after one more case of dengue fever was
confirmed in Townsville. There are now 6 cases, all of them in the
suburb of Cranbrook.
[During January 2006], a family of 4 contracted the mosquito-borne
illness and there have been 2 more cases in the past 2 weeks.
John Piispanen from the Tropical Population Health Unit says there is
still the potential for dengue to spread across the city.
"The other item of concern is that officers from Townsville,
Thuringowa and ourselves are still finding significant amounts of
breeding out there, and that just means that [there is] the potential
for dengue to spread, and it will spread quickly from here if we
can't contain it, the potential is still there," he said.
"So the message to the public [is] still the same, I suppose the good
one for north Queensland is 'just don't get bitten by a mosquito.'"
--
