[6] Colombia
Date: Mon, 13 Feb 2006 07:45:01 -0500 (EST)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: The Daily Journal, Caracas, Venezuela, 13 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://www.thedailyjournalonline.com/article.asp?
ArticleId=224275&CategoryId=12393>

The Colombian city of Yopal was trying to stem a dengue outbreak that
has already claimed the life of an 11-month-old baby, health
officials said Friday. "We're facing an emergency," said Dr. Juan
Eduardo Duran, director of the main hospital in Yopal, 210 kilometers
west of Bogota.
An outbreak of the mosquito-borne disease is common during the summer
months of January and February in Yopal, where the city's 100 000
mostly poor residents deposit water in open-air tanks, the doctor
said. But since the start of the year, the city has reported 23 cases
of the more lethal dengue haemorrhagic fever, compared to just 5
during all of 2005.
"Everything is pointing an epidemic of great proportions," Duran told the
Associated Press. To control the spread of the disease, officials have begun
fumigating the town. An 11-month-old baby boy died in a Bogota hospital in
late January [2006] after doctors in Yopal struggled for 5 days to keep him
alive.
