[8] Indonesia
Date: Thu, 16 Feb 2006 06:43:05 -0500 (EST)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: The Jakarta Post, Indonesia, 16 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://www.thejakartapost.com/detailnational.asp?fileid=20060216.D02&irec=3>

A 2-year-old girl has been diagnosed with dengue fever, but due to
the rising number of dengue fever patients at local hospitals, she is
confined to a cot in a corridor of the hospital. Her 38-year-old
mother stays by her side.
"During visiting hours, the corridor will be full with people passing
through, but what can I do? All the treatment rooms are full," the
mother explained.
The number of dengue fever patients at the hospital, according to
director Mulyo Hartono, has risen markedly throughout February 2006.
Over the last 4 weeks, his hospital has treated 87 dengue patients.
"Starting 5 Feb 2006, dengue patients keep coming in and the
available rooms are limited," Mulyo said.
Most of the patients, he said, were children, while the children's
ward could only accommodate 20 patients. "Today, there are at least
35 pediatric patients with dengue at the hospital, so more than a
dozen have just been put out in the hallway," he said.
Meanwhile, the head of Yogyakarta's health agency, Choirul Anwar,
blamed the rise in dengue cases on local residents, who he claimed
had been negligent in keeping their surroundings clean.
"We've visited (dengue fever) patients' houses, and in areas like
Umbulharjo and Giwangan, no houses are free from mosquito larvae. Out
of 100 houses visited, all had areas where larvae were growing,"
Choirul told The Jakarta Post by phone.
[Byline: Slamet Susanto]
